<p><strong>Trowbridge’s Shrew (<em>Sorex trowbridgii</em>)</strong></p>
<p><strong>Family: </strong>Soricidae<br />
<strong>Genus Species: </strong><em>Sorex trowbridgii</em><br />
<strong>Common Name: </strong>Trowbridge’s Shrew<br /><p>
<p><strong>Identification</strong></p>
<p>The Trowbridge’s Shrew has a body size between 2½-2⅘ inches, a tail size between 2-2½ inches, and a weight ranging from 6-9 grams. This shrew is a relatively large shrew and is nearly uniform in color (dark mouse-gray to brownish). It has a distinctly bi-colored tail and is nearly white below. For a more detailed overview of this species see 〔<a href="http://www.enature.com/fieldguides/detail.asp?shapeID=1034&amp;curGroupID=5&amp;lgfromWhere=&amp;curPageNum=11" target="_blank">eNature</a>〕.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong>Habitat Associations and Natural History</strong></p>
<p>This mammal can be found in coniferous forests and other wooded areas. Little is known about the Trowbridge’s Shrew’s breeding habits except that young are born most frequently (in bunches of 3-6) between March-May, and occasionally in July. This shrew’s diet consists of insects, isopods, other small invertebrates, and Douglas fir seeds. Few live as long as 18 months.</p>
